CONTEXT: I'm building MallPark 360, a Smart Parking Management System 
for a mall, currently in concept/design phase (DFD diagrams across 
3 levels, RazorPay integration already planned). I want to add AI 
features to the app itself and need to decide which parts should be 
AI-powered vs. traditional rule-based logic.
```

DECISION TEST — apply this to any candidate feature:
1. Is the decision pattern-based (predicting/recognizing/ranking) 
   or rule-based (fixed if-X-then-Y logic)? Pattern-based → AI fits.
2. Does it need to handle ambiguous/messy input (images, natural 
   language, variable conditions)? If yes → AI fits.
3. Can I justify the AI choice in one sentence to an examiner? If 
   not, don't use AI there.
```

GOAL: A short, defensible AI scope — 1-2 AI features max, each with:
- A one-line justification (why AI beats simpler logic here)
- A defined data contract (input → output)
- A build-vs-integrate call (train small model vs. call existing API)
- A clear slot in the DFD (new process + data store/external entity)
```

WORK BREAKDOWN:
1. Full feature inventory of the app (human-led — I know the scope)
2. Sort each feature via the decision test (AI can draft, I review)
3. Narrow to 1-2 AI features (human-led — my call, my timeline)
4. Define data contracts for chosen features (AI can draft)
5. Build vs. integrate decision per feature (human-led — depends on 
   my skill level and time)
6. Place into DFD (collaborative — AI drafts placement, I correct 
   against actual diagram)
7. Write one-line justifications myself (human-led — must be able 
   to defend these live)
```

CANDIDATE AI FEATURES DISCUSSED SO FAR:
- Slot demand prediction (ML, uses historical occupancy data)
- License plate recognition (CV/OCR, entry-exit logging)
- Dynamic pricing suggestions
- Support chatbot (NLP)
```

FEATURES TO KEEP RULE-BASED (not AI):
- Slot availability tracking (DB state)
- Booking/reservation logic (deterministic)
- Payment processing via RazorPay (must stay auditable, no AI)
- Navigation to assigned slot (pathfinding algorithm)
- Admin dashboard/reporting (aggregation/queries)
```

